We were notified by Gary Schenkel, OEMC, that a gas line was broke and that gas was being turned off to potentially a three block area in the neighborhood.  Potentially up to 1,000 residents could be displaced.  An ICP was set up at the fire station across the street from the affected buildings at 24th and Kedzie.  SBU Emily Krettler was sent to the scene to offer ARC assistance and to monitor the incident.  It became apparent that only two or three buildings ultimately had their gas cut off and that residents should have services returned by 5:00PM.  Krettler of scene at 2:40PM.

Jim McGowan

JO DAVIESS COUNTY (WREX) -
Heavy, black smoke is billowing from a train derailment about three miles south of Galena.  It happened near the Galena river, south of Ferry Landing Road.

The BNSF train derailed around 1:20 this afternoon, according to Michael Trevino, a rail official.  The train was carrying 105 loaded cars. Of those, 103 of them were carrying crude oil.

Galena City Administrator Mark Moran said there have been no evacuations ordered because the area where this happened is very remote.  No injuries have been reported either.  Moran said the train employees were accounted for and fine.

Moran said around a dozen first responders from Galena and the surrounding counties first arrived at the scene to take stock of what happened.

"There are 8 tanker cars that are off the track," said Moran.  "Two of those are still standing upright.  Six of them are not and are either on their side or upside down.  One of those cars is smoking."

Moran said due to the volatile situation, the crews were ordered to pull back and head to the incident command center off Highway 20.  Then, once BNSF took over the investigation, Moran said the Galena first responders were called off the incident.

A spokeswoman for the Illinois Environmental Protection Agency said it is responding to the derailment as are federal EPA agents.

LaSalle County
In response to flooding occurring along the Illinois River, we will be opening a shelter at the Salvation Army at 516 W Madison St in Ottawa to assist with the evacuation of Marseilles and Utica.  The shelter will be managed in partnership with the Salvation Army.  Historical models lead us to believe that 50 clients or less will be seeking shelter.  However, we should be able to support additional folks if needed.  At the time we will be providing the cots, blankets and food. Joyce Cook, Mark Gephardt and Steve Swett are already active on the response and will be assisting with the initial standup of the shelter.  Mark Gephardt and Emily Krettler will continue to support our liaising with the LaSalle EMA.  

Whiteside County
Also at this time we are continuing to support the distribution of water in Rock Falls (Whiteside County).  This is following the suspension of water supply in the city due to flood-related contamination.  It is unclear when the water service will resume but we anticipate it occurring sometime tomorrow.  7 volunteers have been active throughout the day in supporting multiple distribution points in partnership with the City of Rock Falls.  All of the water has been donated in-kind by Wal-Mart and Kroger.  Later this afternoon and evening we will be delivering cases of water directly to 3 assisted-living facilities in the city.  Leslie Mastroianni is at the EOC in Rock Falls supporting the operation and Mike O’Brien is overseeing the distribution efforts.

Possible Escalation
In addition to the responses listed above, we have also received over 10 flood calls from around the region since this time yesterday.  While these are the current needs that we are aware of, there is the potential of flooding as rainwaters continue to flow downstream.  We may see additional response needs, including sheltering, develop over the next 48 hours as rivers rise further and more rainfall takes place.  Further messaging will come out later today to the full DCS team as the strategy for a potential escalation is developed.

CHICAGO (WLS) -- 
 Two Chicago police officers and a firefighter suffered minor smoke inhalation after they searched a home that caught fire in the city's West Pullman neighborhood.

The officers, who are in their 30s, searched a house in the 12400-block of South State Street around 4 a.m. Thursday after a neighbor reported seeing smoke.


Police said after the officers breathed in too much smoke, they were taken to MetroSouth Medical Center as a precaution. They are expected to be OK.

The fire was extinguished in less than an hour. The firefighter was treated at the scene.

The home was empty.

Call from Kankakee FD requesting ARC services for apartment building fire. 2 victims taken to Loyola Hospital. 

Five people including two young children were hospitalized and at least 22 people were displaced after a fire in suburban Kankakee overnight, authorities said.

The fire in the 800 block of West Station Street also injured a firefighter, who was not taken to a hospital, according to fire chief Ron Young.

A 2-year-old and a 4-year-old were injured and taken to Northwestern Memorial Hospital and Loyola University Medical Center. A man who jumped from the second floor of the building was also hospitalized, along with two women who were injured.

A firefighter was hurt in the process of battling the fire but was not taken to a hospital.

A 39-unit multi-address courtyard building was impacted by a large fire early this morning. We have been on scene since 3AM phasing responders in and out to support a reception center opened for those affected. It is located at Russell Square Park (3045 E 83rd St, Chicago, IL 60617) and is being run in coordination with OEMC and the Chicago Park District. The facility will be staffed by caseworkers and DMH volunteers. In addition, we will be providing 3 meals and snacks.

Of the 39 units, 25 units were deemed not-livable by CFD. 21 of those 25 units are occupied. (See drawing in attachments tab, which shows building and addresses)

The fire was started in the 8112 Essex and 8114 Essex portion of the building and all of those units are destroyed. 

The 8110 Essex and 8108 Essex part of the building is majorly damaged and is also considered not-livable. 

8106 Essex and 8104 Essex part of the building was evacuated, but it seems as though residents will be able to return to their homes tonight after minor repairs are made. Client's may or may not require DCA depending on determination and ability for clients to return home. 

8100 Essex and 8102 Essex units are livable and clients can stay in their homes. No DCA needed. 

All E 81st Street address units are livable and clients can stay in their homes. No DCA needed.

Call from Dominic Tinder (708-527-8389) requesting assistance following a kitchen fire in his home. He, his wife and three children are displaced and staying at a neighbor's house. The Harvey Fire Department was NOT called to respond.

NOTE: if calls come in for assistance, please check the family name against the tenant list (see attachments) and clients who requested assistance on 11/23/16 (clients tab). Placeholders for families that requested help, but missed the reception center on 11/23/16 are found on the clients tab. 

SUMMARY: 
Fire occurred around 0230 on 11/23/16; displacing a total of 81 people residing in 39 units at 5 Times Square Rd in Elgin, IL. 

Red Cross dispatch received notification of incident around 0745 on 11/23/16. Responders were then dispatched to the apartment complex and later opened a casework reception center at the Hemmens Cultural Center, located at 45 Symphony Drive in Elgin, IL. 

18 families received services at the center (35 adults and 13 children) with a sign posted directing additional requests to contact our dispatch line to schedule an appointment to meet with responders over the holiday weekend. See clients tab for details on families served on scene and placeholders for families that expressed a need for services, but missed the team on 11/23/16. Immediate DCA can be provided to the residents of building 5 through 11/30/16 should anyone call requesting help. See the tenant list in the attachments tab for full names of building residents. 

Building is uninhabitable due to electricity and heat being turned off after the fire. To turn on utilities, inspections must be completed by the Fire Marshal and the City of Elgin's building department. See timeline for next steps with Fire Marshal inspection. 

Many residents are Spanish speaking, have access or functional needs or are from a lower socio-economic status. Full family details and outstanding needs are located in client records in CAS. 

Given the Thanksgiving holiday and upcoming weekend, it was estimated by the Building Management company that the soonest residents would be able to re enter the building would be Monday, 11/28/16. 

Responders to the scene and casework center provided DCA plus lodging to the families impacted by this incident. Additional follow up work will be completed by the casework and recovery team.

UPDATE (12/15/16 10:15 PM):
Per Erin Stephens, we are opening a shelter:
Homer Glenn Junior High School 
15711 South Bell Rd Homer Glen, IL 60491
____________________

A large gas explosion has occurred in Homer Glen resulting in multiple injuries.  One home has been destroyed with at least 2 others directly affected.  An evacuation has been ordered for the surrounding neighborhood due to a related gas leak.  A team of 6 Red Crossers are on scene at a Reception Center opened at the address below.  

Hot meals and beverages will be provided at the reception center for response personnel and displaced residents until the evacuation order is lifted.  We will be closely monitoring this situation as it develops and will place a shelter on standby if it appears the evacuation will last through the night.

ABC7 is on scene and other media outlets have been reporting on the story.  Our PIO, Cat Rabenstine, has been actively working with media and posting on social media regarding the response.  Jeremiah is the DAT Captain on scene and will be leading the response with the support of 3 DAT Leads and 2 DAT Trainees.  

Reception Center:
Homer Glen Village Hall
14240 W 151st St

Alerted by OEMC to a residential fire at 15:30 causing 5 displacements, 1F, 1M, 3 teenagers.

This fire occurred in a 20-unit apartment building, which has addresses encompassing 1404-1418 E 73rd St.

Fire started in 1406 building and damaged 1404 and 1406 addresses. The clients in the two 1404 units declined assistance on scene, they had some smoke damage. The clients in two 1406 received DCA - see client tab.

The remainder of the building is livable and not impacted by fire, however, the hot water was turned off to all units. DAT believes the fire originated at one of the hot water units and there was a gas safety concern. People's gas was on scene.  

If clients call requesting assistance for their hot water, no DCA to be issued in these circumstances. Tenants should work w/ insurance and gas company to get hot waters checked and turned back on.

The units where the gas was cut entirely were units where the residents were not on scene. If those clients call in requesting assistance they should be directed to call the gas company and have their gas restored. If the gas company is unable to turn gas back on or is unable to do so until Monday, those clients may be eligible for some assistance - contact DAT Captain to verify.

The cause of the fire and death are under investigation. The fire was contained to the garage and there is no apparent damage."

Per correspondence from Admin: 
Earlier today our team responded to home fire which sadly involved the passing of a Chicago Fire Department paramedic. He also served as a lieutenant with the Homewood Fire Department. It is unclear what caused the fatality but it does not appear that it was directly related to the fire. There were no residents present at the scene but it is believed that one was taken to an area hospital. Our responders left door hangers at the address and the team will be following up to ensure services are available to any residents who may have been displaced. We will also be in touch with the Chicago and Homewood Fire Departments to extend condolences and offer any support that may be needed. The DMH team will also follow up with the volunteers who responded to the event.

OGLE COUNTY - Six people died during an early morning house fire in Ogle County.

Several fire departments responded to 204 N. Miami Dr. in Lost Nation just after midnight, just north of the Lee County line. When firefighters arrived, the home was completely engulfed in flames. Eight different departments were on scene, but all six people inside died.

The victim's names have not been released at this time. Police and the State Fire Marshall's Office are investigating the cause.

Due to ongoing recovery services we have now reached a Level II response for a fire that occurred on December 7th. This was in the West Pullman neighborhood on Chicago’s far south side. 19 elderly clients were displaced as heavy fire and water damage shut down the large senior living center  on 12045 South Emerald Avenue. The property management company provided hotel stays for the first three days following the fire but were unable to continue that support and the building remained inaccessible due to the fire.

On Monday, a team of five Red Crossers opened a small reception center and provided lodging assistance for the displaced individuals. Throughout the week, we continued to work with the management company to determine when the clients would be able to return to their homes and if any other resources were available. Yesterday we learned that repairs on the building were taking longer than expected and that the majority of clients would be unable to return until early next week. Based on this, a determination was made to provide supplemental assistance to those who were running out of funds to continue staying at the hotel until they’re homes were repaired. 

The CAS Event number for this incident was originally IL1217-FIR-83, but it now has a DR Number 480-18. Any future cases should be opened using that number.

The Red Cross responded to a tragic fatal fire early this morning in Chicago's Logan Square neighborhood. The deceased was a 64 year-old woman and mother of two. She was wheelchair-bound and died on the second floor of the building. The fire department found that none of the smoke alarms were functional in the building. Two DAT responders responded to the scene and provided assistance to the four surviving family members who were displaced. Fortunately there were no other injuries as a result of the fire. We will continue to assist the affected family through casework, health and mental health services over the coming weeks. Reactive preparedness will also be explored for the neighborhood.

Initial notification per social media: Chicago - Still and Box Alarm now @ 5750 N Kenmore. 5 sty apartment building.
____________________

In response to a 2-alarm fire that significantly damaged a 72-unit apartment building, we are opening a shelter in the Edgewater Beach neighborhood on Chicago's North side.

The fire occurred at 5750 N Kenmore Ave around 8:45 PM. Multiple Red Cross responders arrived on scene at 9:45. 

It is estimated that more than 50 people and a dozen pets will need overnight accommodations.

The Episcopal Church of the Atonement, across the street at 5749 N Kenmore Ave, has graciously opened it doors to the displaced residents and is currently permitting it's reception hall to be used as an evacuation center. Shelter accommodations will be set up in an adjacent gymnasium. There are two Disaster Mental Health responders on scene. There are no urgent medical needs, however, Health Services will be required on scene tomorrow morning. Meals and infant supplies are en route to the facility.

Wilson Chow will serve as Shelter Manager.

Red cross responded to large scale apartment fire. Up to 52 units affected. Shelter survey being conducted at this time. Responders on scene. 

Incident Report:
Incident Address: 305 Woodcreek Dr, Bolingbrook, IL
Shelter: Bolingbrook High School, 365 Raider Way, Bolingbrook, IL (Enter at Door 17)
Reception Center: River Stone Apartments, 308 Woodcreek Dr, Bolingbrook, IL


Situation Summary:
At approximately 1:30AM this morning, we were notified by social media of a fire in a 52-unit apartment building on Woodcreek Dr in Bolingbrook. Initially, it was not known if Red Cross services were needed, however, shortly after 2:30AM, responders were requested. By 4:30AM, it was determined that at least 16 units had been affected. 

Our teams have been on the scene at a Reception Center opened in the River Stone Apartments clubhouse meeting with and assisting those affected. Apartment management has vacant units which they have allocated to 14 families. As the units are unfurnished, the Red Cross has provided cots, blankets and comfort items.
 
Thirty-eight additional families have displaced: two by fire damage, the rest due to utilities being shut off. As a result, we have opened a shelter at Bolingbrook High School located at 365 Raider Way.
 
We have staff available to assist through the night to support this operation. Wilson Chow will be the Shelter Manager this evening and will transition to Judy Gustafson who will cover overnight operations. The shelter opening has been recorded in NSS. The shelter will remain open until 8AM tomorrow. Building management will utilize their resources to provide additional sheltering/feeding assistance to the 38 families. Except for the 16 impacted families, there is no anticipation that further casework assistance will be needed.

Yesterday ARC responded to a cold home fire in the 8600 block of South Honore, Auburn Gresham, Chicago. It is with regret that we advise that a 24-year-old man passed away as a result of the fire.

No family or relatives were on site, consequently ARC responders spoke to neighbors to collect contact information.

The deceased was living alone at the time with his mother and father out of town. Responders left a door hanger at the incident and will follow up as per SOP.

DLOC will request:
--- DHS to assess if funeral assistance required
--- Region Preparedness Manager to assess if this home had been visited during  the recent June 2018 Sound the Alarm rally that focused on this neighborhood

Due to intial OEMC feedback and concerns that the incident was a potential criminal investigation, and that no family were at the scene we purposefully held back responding until facts were established later in the day.

Media reported the following:

"A man and a dog were found dead Friday morning after a kitchen fire in a South Side Gresham neighborhood home, officials said. A family member found the 24-year-old man dead shortly after 10:30 a.m. inside the home in the 8600 block of South Honore, according to Fire Media Affairs director Larry Langford. The fire apparently started when the man fell asleep while food was cooking in the kitchen, Langford said. It burned itself out at some point before the man was discovered. 

The fire generated “heavy smoke and carbon monoxide” inside the home, according to the fire department. The relative had gone to the house to check on the man and found him dead near a dog, which was also dead, Langford said. Preliminary investigation indicated the man may have woken up at some point and tried to get the dog out of the home, but was unable to make it out. 

The Cook County Medical Examiner’s Office had not released details about the death as of Friday afternoon. It was not immediately clear what time the fire occurred, but it may have started between 10 p.m. Thursday and sometime Friday morning, according to Langford. Smoke detectors were present and working in the house. The fire remained under investigation."

Fatal Home Fire, Rockford, IL. One death and Eight survivors.

The Rockford Fire Department requested ARC responded to a house fire in the 700 block of Winnebago Street around 5:45 this morning. 

Flames were showing from the second floor of the home. Fire crews searched the house after reports of a two year old child in the building, with an active search and rescue taking place.

Firefighters were able to find and rescue the child, who was taken to the hospital in critical condition. The child later died as a result of their injuries.

It was determined that the clients could be best served by coming to the ARC Chapter office where their privacy and needs could be better met.

The ARC commenced provided services (non-livable and lodging) totalling $1,465 for the eight surviving family members. Comfort kits and colouring books for the children were also offered.

Clients are likely to require DMH, DHS and funeral services.

No other injuries have been reported at this time. 

The neighborhood in which the fire occured had been part of this years StA campaign. An initial check of our StA database indicates that the affected home was unable to be visited.

Media report that the scene is still under investigation.

A big thank you to our responding team of Linda Griffin, Brad Polnow, Mike O'Brien, Harold Cubillo and Brian Nestler.
